# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] The **1966 Asian Games**, also known as the **V Asiad** or **Bangkok 1966**, were a continental multi-sport event that was held from 9 to 20 December 1966, in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] A total of 142 events in 16 sports were contested by athletes during the games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] Taiwan and Israel returned to the Asian Games, reversing the decision taken by Indonesia in the previous Asiad to debar the two countries.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] A total number of 2,500 athletes and officials from 18 countries, were involved in this Asiad.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] The 5th Asiad was the first one where women's volleyball was played.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] Japan led the medal table for the fifth consecutive time, and they gained a new record for the most gold medals in a single Asian Games since 1962 in Jakarta.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1966-asian-games] The host nation, Thailand, is highlighted.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] The **6th Asian Games** also known as **Bangkok 1970**, were held from 9 to 20 December 1970 in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] Seoul, South Korea, had been selected to host the 6th Games but it declined due to both financial reasons and security threats from neighboring North Korea (the city eventually hosted in 1986).
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] The previous host, Thailand, stepped in to save the Asiad.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] 2,400 athletes from 18 countries competed in this Asiad, where yachting made its debut.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 1970 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] The numeral indicates the number of event finals for each sport held that day.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] On the left, the calendar lists each sport with events held during the Games, and at the right, how many gold medals were won in that sport.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1970-asian-games] There is a key at the top of the calendar to aid the reader.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] The **8th Asian Games** (Thai: กีฬาเอเชียนเกมส์ครั้งที่ 8), also known as **Bangkok 1978** (Thai: กรุงเทพมหานคร 1978), were held from 9 to 20 December 1978, in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] Originally, the host city was Singapore but Singapore dropped its plan to host the Games due to financial problems.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] Then Islamabad, the capital of Pakistan, was decided to host the 8th Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] But Islamabad also dropped its plan to host the Asian Games due to conflicts with Bangladesh and India.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] The Imperial State of Iran withdrew because of the Iranian revolution.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] Thailand offered to help and the Asiad therefore was held in Bangkok.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] On the political front, Israel was expelled from the Asian Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] A total number of 3,842 athletes, coming from 25 countries, competed in these Asian Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] Debuting sports were archery and bowling.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] 25 out of 32 Olympic Council of Asia members participated in these games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] Iran sent only one official and did not participate in the games due to the political situation in Iran at the time.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1978-asian-games] Democratic Kampuchea also did not send any athletes and were represented by two officials.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The sporting events commenced on 30 November 1998, a week earlier than the opening ceremony.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] It is a last time that the multi-sport event would be held in Bangkok until the 2007 Summer Universiade.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] Bangkok was awarded the right on September 26, 1990, defeating Taipei, Taiwan and Jakarta, Indonesia to host the Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] It was the first city to hosted the Asian Games for four times, but was the first time that the city make a bid to host.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The last three editions it hosted were in 1966, 1970 and 1978 (in the latter two cases stepping in to prevent the Games from being cancelled due to problems with the elected hosts).
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The event was opened by Bhumibol Adulyadej, the king of Thailand, at the Rajamangala Stadium.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The final medal tally was led by China, followed by South Korea, Japan and the host Thailand.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] Thailand set a new record with 24 gold medals.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] Japanese Athletics Koji Ito was announced as the most valuable player (MVP) of the Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] For Thailand, it was considered one of its remarkable achievement in sports development throughout the country's modern history.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] Three cities placed a bid for the Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] All three, Taipei (Taiwan), Jakarta (Indonesia) and Bangkok (Thailand) submitted their formal bid in 1989.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] It was the first time that Thailand has presented a bid for host the Asian Games, as Bangkok was the default host of previous three games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The vote was held on September 27, 1990, at the China Palace Tower Hotel in Beijing, China, during the 9th Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) General Assembly held during the 1990 Asian Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] All 37 members voted, with voting held in secret ballot.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] It was announced that Bangkok won an Asian Games bid process for the first time.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] Though the vote results were not released, was leaked to the press that Bangkok won by 20–10–7.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] Bangkok became the first city to have staged the Asian Games for four editions, following 1966, 1970 and 1978, and this was the first time that the city had put a bid for the event.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] According to United Press International news report, preparations for the games including the construction and renovation of three main stadiums and an athletes' village, cost an estimated 6 billion Thai baht (US$167 million).
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The official emblem of the games combines elements from Thai stupas and pagodas, the letter "A", which means either "Asia" or "Athletes", and the logo of the Olympic Council of Asia.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] It symbolises the knowledge, intelligence and athletic prowess of Thailand.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The official mascot of the games is an elephant named **Chai-Yo** (ไชโย), the equivalent of "hurrah" in Thai.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] Elephants are known and admired among Thais for their strength and nobility.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The opening ceremony started at 17:00 local time on December 6, 1998.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] It was attended by King of Thailand, Bhumibol Adulyadej, President of the International Olympic Committee Juan Antonio Samaranch and President of the OCA Sheikh Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] The nations entered in alphabetic order of their country names in Thai during the parade of nations.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-asian-games] National Olympic Committees (NOCs) are named according to their official IOC designations and arranged according to their official IOC country codes in 1998.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The **1st Asian Indoor Games** were held in Bangkok, Thailand from November 12 to 19, 2005.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The sun is the symbol of the Olympic Council of Asia.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The redline, the blue line and the golden line forming like an "A" shape, together with a Thai roof, represent the Asian continent and the Asian Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The golden line that resembling Thai smile, expressing a warm welcome to visitors.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] Each sport discipline is animated with an elephant, thus giving the appearance of its cartoon movements in all events to be competed in the 1st Asian Indoor Games 2005.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] Children and other people alike will be fond of them, pleasant to look at them and keeping them for a souvenir after the end of the Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The blue and athletic elephant was named Hey and the yellow and plump one was Há.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] They were to convey the meaning of amusement, merriment and relaxation, thus in a way reflecting the natures of the Asian Indoor Games a great deal.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] There are 37 Asian countries confirmed to participate in the game.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] The **2007 Asian Indoor Games** (Chinese: 2007年亞洲室內運動會; Portuguese: *Jogos Asiáticos em Recinto Coberto de 2007*), officially known as the **2nd Asian Indoor Games** and also known as **Macau 2007**, were held in Macau, China from 26 October 2007 to 3 November 2007.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] Most events of the games took place at the Macao East Asian Games Dome.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] The Emblem of the 2nd Asian Indoor Games gives an overall impression of the sun shining above the covered gymnasium.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] There were 44 Asian countries confirmed to participate in the games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] A total of 17 sports were scheduled to be competed in this edition of the Indoor Asiad.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] The following is a list of the sports and the number of the designated events in parentheses.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] Bangkok, Saskatoon, Poznań, Kaohsiung and Monterrey were the five candidate cities.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] The official mascot of the 2007 Summer Universiade is a rabbit named *Mighty Mai-Tri*.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] The name of this mascot suggests themes of power and friendship but also corresponds to the Year of the Rabbit, which is the lunar year of King Bhumibol's birth.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] The rabbit welcomes athletes of all nations.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] His appearance expresses humility through a smile, color, and mannerism.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] The slogan for the 24th Summer Universiade is, "All Become One", suggesting the unity of people of all races and religions from 150 countries.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] The logo itself consists of five line colors arranged in a U shape, which is derived from the word *Universiade* and is comparable to the lines of experience transmission.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] The exchange of knowledge and culture between representatives and athletes from universities from five continents around the world all in one.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-summer-universiade] Connected into a golden yellow bird patterned symbol, which is the identity of the Thai nation.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) officially awarded the Games to Bangkok and Chonburi Province and signed the hosting rights contract in April 2020.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Originally scheduled to take place from 21 to 30 May 2021, the event was postponed four times due to various occasions.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It was pushed back twice as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic, first rescheduled to be held from 10 to 20 March 2022, and then from 17 to 26 November 2023.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] However, the event was postponed again due to political uncertainty in the country following the Thai general election; the Games were then timetabled for 24 February to 6 March 2024, but were rescheduled once more citing its five-month proximity to the 2024 Summer Olympics in Paris.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] On 19 August 2024, the Games were cancelled after organizers failed to meet contractual obligations.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] However, the OCA Executive Board also agreed that Thailand can apply to host the next games after the 2025 edition.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] This edition of the AIMAG would have marked the debuts for badminton, baseball5, BMX cycling, cheerleading, floorball, indoor rowing, netball, shooting and volleyball, and would have seen a record-high number of sports in the event's history, at a total of 30.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] On November 28, National Olympic Committee of Thailand (NOCT) President Yuthasak Sasiprapha initially expressed possible of Thai's Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games bid in 2021 to OCA Director General Husain A.H.Z.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Al-Musallam during 2015 ANOC General Assembly in the United States.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] During the 2019 OCA General Assembly in Bangkok, Thailand had expressed interest to bid for four major sporting events between 2021 and 2030, namely the 2021 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games, the Asian Youth Games in 2025, the Summer Youth Olympics in 2026, and the 2030 Asian Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The OCA chose Bangkok and Chonburi on 27 April 2020 in a virtual meeting, and the host city contract is signed that same day.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The cabinet resolution was released on March 17, 2020.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It reported the negotiations with the Olympic Council of Asia and the budget allocation for the Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The Olympic Council of Asia reduced a cost of marketing right from ~US$2 million to ~US$500 thousand.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It distributed a broadcasting right to two parts that one is a local broadcasting right for the host country and the other one is an international broadcasting right shared the Organizing Committee with 50 percent.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It also allowed Bangkok and Chonburi Province to host the Games as joint host cities.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It also suggested the Organizing Committee to provide more budget for Coronavirus disease 2019 prevention management by Ministry of Tourism and Sports and Ministry of Public Health.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The OCA Coordination Committee, permanent committee not depending on any Games, will be responsible for the conduct of the five different Games organised by the Olympic Council of Asia.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It is headed by Randhir Singh elected for the period 2019 to 2023, during the 38th OCA General Assembly held in Bangkok.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The meeting of the preparation of the 6th Asian Indoor and Martial Art Games was held on June 15, 2020.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Chaipak Siriwat, vice president of the Olympic Council of Asia, informed officially about competition programme confirmed by the Olympic Council of Asia.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It was confirmed that the Games will be held between 21 and 30 May, including consideration of the events in the twenty-nine sports and two demonstration sports proposed by the Organizing Committee.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Fourteen sports complexes were also confirmed, including eight in Bangkok and six in Chonburi.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The meeting proposed to launch the Public Health Commission encouraged by Department of Health and Ministry of Public Health.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It recommended Coronavirus disease 2019 preventive measures in two ways depended on whether the pandemic is over or not.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] One is to allow athletes and officials quarantining for fourteen days, before the curtain will rise on the Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Five sport events would have been held at the SAT Sports Complex, which were some of the main venues of the 1966, 1970, 1978, and 1998 Asian Games, the 2005 Asian Indoor Games, the 2007 Summer Universiade, and the 2009 Asian Martial Arts Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Three sport events will be held at the National Stadium and Chulalongkorn University, which were some of the main venues of the 1966, 1970, 1978, and 1998 Asian Games, the 2005 Asian Indoor Games, the 2007 Summer Universiade, and the 2009 Asian Martial Arts Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Two sport events will be held at the Bangkok Youth Center (Thai-Japan), which were some of the main venues of the 1998 Asian Games, the 2005 Asian Indoor Games, the 2007 Summer Universiade, and the 2009 Asian Martial Arts Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Two sport events will be held at the Assumption University Suvarnabhumi Campus in surrounding Samut Prakan Province, which were some of the main venues of the 2007 Summer Universiade.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Thirteen sport events will be held in Pattaya City, which were some of the main venues of the 2005 Asian Indoor Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The article 74 of the Olympic Council of Asia constitution states that the programme of the AIMAG shall include not less than six indoor sports and two sports from martial arts sports, recognised by the Olympic Council of Asia.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] For this to happen, it will be a responsibility of the organizing committee to choose which of twenty-nine sports included within the status of indoor sports or martial arts sports and not part in latest editions of the Asian Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The organizing committee can choose any sports part in latest editions of the Asian Games or not within the status of indoor sports or martial arts sports, if there are demands from the host country.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] On 21 May 2020, the Olympic Council of Asia and the organizing committee announced the final number of sports on this edition's program with finals being held in twenty eight sports, seven more than those held in the previous edition in 2017.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The number of sports programme increased to twenty-nine sports after successful negotiations to add Olympic and Asian Games sports who are very popular at the country as shooting, badminton and volleyball, but this sports have to held non-olympic events.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Due to a ban imposed by the International Weightlifting Federation on Thailand, weightlifting events have to be excluded.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] A total of thirty-two disciplines in thirty sports and two demonstration sports were scheduled to be included before the Games were cancelled.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Cheerleading, Floorball, Indoor rowing and Netball are sports that have recently been approved by International Olympic Committee and are on the World Games program and have low popularity and visibity in certain regions of Asia.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] However, in other countries or regions of the continent they are extremely popular.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Going according to the original proposal of the event, this was their chance to be part of the sports program of a multisport event, which certainly would have increased their visibility on the continent and increase the chances that they would be included in the Olympic Games program in the future.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Among these, four were new sports (badminton, shooting, volleyball and water polo).
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Although they are part of the Asian Games programme too, the organizing committee would have revamped the events to differ from current Asian Games programme.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Badminton events would have been reduced from 7 at the Asian Games to 3, for example The number of events in the shooting would've also dropped from 20 to just 5, only the pistol events (10 and 25 meters) were scheduled to be held.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Changes were also planned in volleyball tournaments.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Each participating team would have been able to register 12 athletes, however, up to 3 athletes may have been over 23 years old.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Another specific case is that of sepak takraw, after 12 years hiatus the sport was planned to be back on the program.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] As the national sport of Thailand, the format of the competitions and the number of events at the last Asian Games would have been maintained.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] In addition, the four events that were excluded from Hangzhou would have bene added, along the hoop and five extra events would have been added to the program.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] On July 16, 2020, the National Olympic Committee of Thailand announced that it proposed to the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) to open the event for athletes from the 24 National Olympic Committees from the Oceania National Olympic Committees (ONOC).
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The proposal was accepted without any reservations by the OCA and the ONOC, as they proved the success on the 2017 Games held in Ashgabat and the 2017 Sapporo Winter Games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The three stakeholders were planning to authorize the registration of athletes in 16 individual sports as an integral part of the games.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] This was the planned calendar at the time of cancellation.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The emblem of the 2021 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games was inspired by the flower garland called Phuang malai, symbolizing the interconnectedness of all participants from all parts of Asia.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Thai garland represents respect, victory, dignity, and the power of hope.
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The official slogan of the games was "Garland of Hope".
[src:2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2021-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The official mascot depicted a fighting parrot wearing a mongkhon (a type of headgear worn by Muay Thai athletes) who has intelligence, agility and a fighting spirit, making a gesture of inviting athletes and sports competitors to the victory of friendship.
